(1343, 600, '_wp_attachment_metadata', 'a:5:{s:5:"width";i:860;s:6:"height";i:320;s:4:"file";s:19:"2014/04/spiegel.jpg";s:5:"sizes";a:2:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:19:"spiegel-150x150.jpg";s:5:"width";i:150;s:6:"height";i:150;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}s:6:"medium";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:18:"spiegel-255x94.jpg";s:5:"width";i:255;s:6:"height";i:94;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}}s:10:"image_meta";a:10:{s:8:"aperture";i:0;s:6:"credit";s:3:"dpa";s:6:"camera";s:0:"";s:7:"caption";s:468:"epa04168538 A general view of several tents placed where houses used to be prior to a fire at Las Canas hill, in Valparaiso, Chile, 15 April 2014. Hundreds of firemen and volunteers continued to try to extinguish the remaining fires affecting the area since 12 April 2014. The fires have left a death toll of 15 and 11,000 affected people in the Chilean city of Valparaiso, as government plans the reconstruction of the area. EPA/FELIPE TRUEBA +++(c) dpa - Bildfunk+++";s:17:"created_timestamp";i:0;s:9:"copyright";s:0:"";s:12:"focal_length";i:0;s:3:"iso";i:0;s:13:"shutter_speed";i:0;s:5:"title";s:25:"Valparaiso fire aftermath";}}'),
