er Tulio Arce said.Residents and volunteers worked to clear the debris left behind.\r\n\r\n“The only thing we need is help, please, nothing else, because there’s nothing left,” a resident, Ana Maria Espinoza, told the Associated Press news agency.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<ul class="ficha-prensa">\r\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Nacionalidad:</em> Canadiense</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Medio:</em> Online</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Fuente:</em> The Globe and Mail</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Fecha:</em> 13/04/2014</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Autor:</em> Graciela Ibanez y Marianela Jarroud</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Tema:</em> relatos o reportajes</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>URL:</em>  <a href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/chiles-historic-valparaiso-in-flames-16-dead-500-homes- destroyed/article17950253/" title="url" target="_blank">http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/chiles-historic-valparaiso-in-flames-16-dead-500-homes- destroyed/article17950253/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 'Chile’s historic Valparaiso in flames; 12 dead and 2,000 homes destroyed', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '210-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-05-07 23:25:29', '2014-05-07 23:25:29', '', 210, 'http://vergel439.cl/2014/05/210-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(466, 5, '2014-05-07 23:25:49', '2014-05-07 23:25:49', '<div class="section">\n<div class="layoutArea">\n<div class="column">\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class="layoutArea">\n<div class="column">\n</div>\n<div class="column">\n\n<strong>Parts of the historic city of Valparaiso have been engulfed by a fire, killing at least 16 people and destroying 500 homes</strong>\n\nA huge fire has roared through the Chilean coastal city of Valparaíso, killing at least 16 people and destroying 500 homes in the historic World Heritage city.\n\nFanned by strong winds from the Pacific, the fire blazed over 1,700 acres of the forests and hilly residential areas that sweep up from the port, and which have given Valparaíso its moniker of the “San Francisco of the South”.\n\n“Valparaiso is without electricity at the moment,” said Jorge Castro, mayor of the city of 270,000, as the fire raged on Saturday night. “This means the flame column is creating a Dante-esque panorama, and is advancing in an apparently uncontrollable manner.”\n\nSome 1,200 firefighters were battling the blaze, using three planes and four helicopters to drop water on the flames, but they were unable to prevent the destruction of entire districts.\n\nAnd by Sunday morning the scale of the devastation was clear.\n\n“This is the worst catastrophe I’ve seen,” said Ricardo Bravo, the regional governor. “Now we have to make sure the fire doesn’t reach the city centre, which would make this emergency much more serious.” Michelle Bachelet, the Chilean president, declared a state of emergency and sent the army in to patrol the streets and prevent looting. “It’s a tremendous tragedy, perhaps the worst fire” in the city’s history, she said.\n\nThe country’s Congress – which has been housed in Valparaíso, rather than the capital Santiago, since the days of General Augusto Pinochet – and the city’s historic quarter, with its late 19th century architecture, were spared by the blaze.\n\nBut as some of the 10,000 evacuated residents begun returning to their hillside homes – many of which were built of wood – they found them burnt to the ground.\n\n“We fled from the La Cruz neighbourhood, from an apartment I just got not too long ago. It’s all burned down, my sister’s house also burnt to the ground,” said Rosa Guzman, visibly upset as she stared helplessly up at the hills.\n\nImages on Chilean television showed bewildered residents sifting through the charred remains of their houses, as planes carrying water buzzed overhead.\n\nFrancisca Granados, who had spent the night with friends in the neighbouring city of Vina del Mar, was shown returning to her home. “It’s frightening, everything is burned,” she said.\nThe city, which became Chile’s first port in 1554, draws tourists to its pastel-coloured wooden buildings, sprawling up the hills. A series of wooden funicular lifts, taking people from the residential hilltops down to the industrial port area, have been declared one of the world’s 100 most endangered historical treasures. And Pablo Neruda, the celebrated Chilean poet, built a clifftop home in the city which he used as a base to write his books.\n\nUntil the construction of the Panama Canal, Valparaíso was a vital port on the Pacific, and in the 1880s\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\nattracted immigrants from Britain, the United States, Germany and Spain. Despite falling into decline in the mid 1900s, in recent years the city has revived and is now a bustling cultural hub with a large student population.\n\nThe fire is the second disaster to befall Chile in the first month of Ms Bachelet’s presidency. Two weeks previously the country was rocked by an earthquake measuring 8.2 on the Richter scale.\n\nBut the president, beginning her second term, said that everything possible would be done to restore the devastated neighbourhoods.\n\n“It’s a terrible scene,” she said. “But the people of Valparaíso are strong and courageous. They are not on their own.”\n<ul class="ficha-prensa">\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Nacionalidad:</em> Inglés</li>\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Medio:</em> Online</li>\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Fuente:</em> The Telegraph</li>\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Fecha:</em> 13/04/2014</li>\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Autor:</em> Harriet Alexander</li>\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>Tema:</em> relatos o reportajes</li>\n<li> <span class=''none''><em>URL:</em>  <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/chile/10764032/Chilean-city-of-Valparaiso- reels-from-fire-This-is-the-worst-catastrophe-Ive-seen.html" title="url" target="_blank">http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/chile/10764032/Chilean-city-of-Valparaiso- reels-from-fire-This-is-the-worst-catastrophe-Ive-seen.html</a></li>\n</ul>\n', 'Chilean city of Valparaiso reels from fire: ‘This is the worst catastrophe I’ve seen’', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '195-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-05-07 23:25:49', '2014-05-07 23:25:49', '', 195, 'http://vergel439.cl/2014/05/195-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(723, 12, '2014-05-08 23:39:33', '2014-05-08 23:39:33', '<img src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/02881/chile_2881181b.jpg" alt="." />\r\n\r\n<strong>Parts of the historic city of Valparaiso have been engulfed by a fire, killing at least 16 people and destroying 500 homes</strong>\r\n\r\nA huge fire has roared through the Chilean coastal city of Valparaíso, killing at least 16 people and destroying 500 homes in the historic World Heritage city.\r\n\r\nFanned by strong winds from the Pacific, the fire blazed over 1,700 acres of the forests and hilly residential areas that sweep up from the port, and which have given Valparaíso its moniker of the “San Francisco of the South”.\r\n\r\n“Valparaiso is without electricity at the moment,” said Jorge Castro, mayor of the city of 270,000, as the fire raged on Saturday night. “This means the flame column is creating a Dante-esque panorama, and is advancing in an apparently uncontrollable manner.”\r\n\r\nSome 1,200 firefighters were battling the blaze, using three planes and four helicopters to drop water on the flames, but they were unable to prevent the destruction of entire districts.\r\n\r\nAnd by Sunday morning the scale of the devastation was clear.\r\n\r\n“This is the worst catastrophe I’ve seen,” said Ricardo Bravo, the regional governor. “Now we have to make sure the fire doesn’t reach the city centre, which would make this emergency much more serious.” Michelle Bachelet, the Chilean president, declared a state of emergency and sent the army in to patrol the streets and prevent looting. “It’s a tremendous tragedy, perhaps the worst fire” in the city’s history, she said.\r\n\r\nThe country’s Congress – which has been housed in Valparaíso, rather than the capital Santiago, since the days of General Augusto Pinochet – and the city’s historic quarter, with its late 19th century architecture, were spared by the blaze.\r\n\r\nBut as some of the 10,000 evacuated residents begun returning to their hillside homes – many of which were built of wood – they found them burnt to the ground.\r\n\r\n“We fled from the La Cruz neighbourhood, from an apartment I just got not too long ago. It’s all burned down, my sister’s house also burnt to the ground,” said Rosa Guzman, visibly upset as she stared helplessly up at the hills.\r\n\r\nImages on Chilean television showed bewildered residents sifting through the charred remains of their houses, as planes carrying water buzzed overhead.\r\n\r\nFrancisca Granados, who had spent the night with friends in the neighbouring city of Vina del Mar, was shown returning to her home. “It’s frightening, everything is burned,” she said.\r\nThe city, which became Chile’s first port in 1554, draws tourists to its pastel-coloured wooden buildings, sprawling up the hills. A series of wooden funicular lifts, taking people from the residential hilltops down to the industrial port area, have been declared one of the world’s 100 most endangered historical treasures. And Pablo Neruda, the celebrated Chilean poet, built a clifftop home in the city which he used as a base to write his books.\r\n\r\nUntil the construction of the Panama Canal, Valparaíso was a vital port on the Pacific, and in the 1880s\r\n\r\nattracted immigrants from Britain, the United States, Germany and Spain. Despite falling into decline in the mid 1900s, in recent years the city has revived and is now a bustling cultural hub with a large student population.\r\n\r\nThe fire is the second disaster to befall Chile in the first month of Ms Bachelet’s presidency. Two weeks previously the country was rocked by an earthquake measuring 8.2 on the Richter scale.\r\n\r\nBut the president, beginning her second term, said that everything possible would be done to restore the devastated neighbourhoods.\r\n\r\n“It’s a terrible scene,” she said. “But the people of Valparaíso are strong and courageous. They are not on their own.”\r\n<ul class="ficha-prensa">\r\n<li> <span class=''none''>Nacionalidad: Inglés</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''>Medio: Online</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''>Fuente: The Telegraph</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''>Fecha: 13/04/2014</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''>Autor: Harriet Alexander</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''>Tema: relatos o reportajes</li>\r\n<li> <span class=''none''>URL: <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/chile/10764032/Chilean-city-of-Valparaiso- reels-from-fire-This-is-the-worst-catastrophe-Ive-seen.html" title="url" target="_blank">http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/chile/10764032/Chilean-city-of-Valparaiso- reels-from-fire-This-is-the-worst-catastrophe-Ive-seen.html</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 'Chilean city of Valparaiso reels from fire: ‘This is the worst catastrophe I’ve seen’', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '195-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-05-08 23:39:33', '2014-05-08 23:39:33', '', 195, 'http://vergel439.cl/2014/05/195-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
